segments.text: We'd lecture one day a week, and then two different days we had sections, a small class deal, and then one afternoon of four hours a week we had a lab.
And by the way, my section professor or instructor at that time turned out to be a friend of mine in later years, Harrington.
M.T.
Harrington?
Yeah.
Oh my.
Describe him as a professor.
Very good.
Very good.
He had a certain charisma about him.
You had to like him.
He had a way of getting you interested
and helping you along, and I thought the world of him.
And after I left his class, I didn't think I'd ever see him again, but it turned out that later on, he and I became great friends.
He used to come down to my place in Laredo, and anyway, he was a fine gentleman, I liked him.
I can't say that for everyone in the chemistry department.
As a sophomore, I'm getting a little ahead, but I'm just saying these things when I remember them.
I had a sophomore professor in comparative, let's see, qualitative analysis.
His name
I don't remember what his first name was, but we called him Wee Willie, Burchard.
I don't question his knowledge of chemistry.
His teaching methods I didn't go much for.
I guess it's an effective way, maybe, but he would ask a question or you would ask a question
And to this day I never heard him give an answer.
I know his method was to probably get you on track to solving it yourself, but this doesn't always, sometimes you need a little help.
He needed a little help.
And he just carried it a little too far as far as I was concerned.
But that's neither here nor there.
He was the teacher and I wasn't.
But anyway, I had a German teacher.
His name was Baetjer, B-A-T-J-E-R.
I got, he taught both first and second year German.
And so when I got into the class, well, I met it first two times, and oh, I was doing well.
And the second time that I met Klaas,
looked at me and he says, , were your parents German?
And I said, no.
I said, they sure weren't.
And he said, well, did you happen to, have you studied German?
I said, well, I had German in high school.
He says, and you used that for entrance credits?
And I said, I'm sure I did.
I probably used everything.
And he says, you're the wrong class.
So they moved me to second year German.
Well, it so happened that in second year German, there was Helmkamp, Wieser.
Everyone in there, with the exception of a fellow named Marshall and myself,
all had German surnames.

And Boettcher knew exactly what was going on because anything that would happen, you know, they'd be more or less asleep in class, but if they had to read something, they'd just point to where and they'd come right out.
And he announced one day, somebody asked him, says,
Mr. Bacher, how do you grade?
What is your grading system?
And he says, I use the curve system.
And Marshall and I are just kind of sunk.
He says, of course, that doesn't apply to Mr. Marshall or Mr. Garner.
I'm going to grade them normally, but the rest of you guys are on the curve system.
Anyway, that took care of him.
I don't remember offhand the
name of my English teacher.
Freshman English was the same, it didn't matter, you know.
And I do remember a sophomore English teacher I had taught a Shakespeare course, very, very interesting.
Who?
Do you remember him?
Seems like they had a nickname for him called Oyster Joe.
No, that's history, Oyster Joe Gammon.
Well, no.
This fellow was kind of a short, heavy-set man, and I can't remember.
Wasn't Cofer?
No, no.
No, it wasn't Cofer.
It was literature and it was practically all Shakespeare.
And he was very, very interesting.
You know, I'd read those Shakespeare plays or stories or whatever it were, and I didn't understand a lot of it.
And when he would read it and explain it, you know, it was then when you started appreciating what Shakespeare was.
But it was kind of difficult for
uneducated boy to know what he was referred to when he made certain colloquialisms of their time that we didn't understand, but that's neither here nor there.
What was the routine for you in terms of regular study?
What was your when and where and how did you prepare for class?
Well, I'm going to have to tell you
something that I hesitate, but it's the truth.
I wasn't the best student in the world.
I mean, let's put it this way.
I had gone through high school, I'd gone through elementary school, everything, high school,
I always made grades.
I never made anything lower than a B the whole time I was in school, and I never studied, which is bad, bad.
Our schools, I think they're getting away from that a lot.
All kids, in high school especially, ought to be challenged so that when they do go, they know how to study.
I had no idea how to study.
And consequently, I didn't study real well.
Sure, I passed the A&M.

didn't get kicked out or anything like that, and I made maybe acceptable grades, but I could have, I know I could have done so much better had I applied myself more, or know how to apply myself, I think.
But also, there's another thing, and we can all, you know, we all look for crutches.
Once December the 7th,
1941 came along.
No, I shouldn't say no one, but very few people in my class had their minds on anything else but what's going to happen here?
What's going to happen here?
We just, we were really in an uncertainty.
That's the first time
that what was going on in the world really came across to us.
And it just affected our schooling very much.
We lived more or less from event to event.
enjoyed pleasant things as much as we could, court trips, football games.
All right, let's venture in that direction.
On the campus, for you as a freshman, describe the routine in the dining hall.
Well, we were in,

Duncan Hall is freshman and We went to the had a table of about ten people at a table About half of them were freshmen and Seniors that the two ends of the table Juniors that if there was no seniors present and
and sophomores at the other places, and your main function was to be sure that they didn't want for anything.
In fact, you were really better off if you didn't start eating until after they were ready to get up and leave, and then you hurriedly ate what you could.
I don't want it to sound like anybody was underfed.
We were not.
Everybody was amply fed.
No kush, no dessert until after a certain day, and every day we'd have to say,
100 days till Cush, or 99 days till Cush.
And if somebody did something wrong, they'd say, that'll be five more days.
So they'd go to 102 days till Cush, which usually went till Thanksgiving, and then everybody got to Cush.
One thing at the dining hall at noon,
That's when they would call out special delivery letters.
And, of course, that was a big thing if your name was called that you had a special delivery letter to pick up.
And they played what we think of now, and I did even then.
I've always been kind of a music buff.
They played the most gorgeous music of the big band era.

at that time the miller and during the meals oh yes really yes nobody's ever mentioned that before yeah really so over a pa system in duncan yes sir yes sir what was the quality of the food it was good really everybody griped you know when people griped about the army food i had wonderful food did you have any favorite aggie foods
No, not really.
Not really.
Was there any that you particularly didn't like?

No, I guess really and truly I was always an eater and I guess that came from my bringing up with at my home my mother put the food on the table and you ate what was on the table and if you didn't like that you didn't say anything about it.
You either ate it or you just
waited until the next meal.
And I never had any problem with the food.
I had a lot of friends that were waiters that kind of take care of you a little bit.
Go ahead.
I was going to say, were there any jokes?
Did you all play any pranks during meals?

Not a whole lot of it really, other than when it came time for fish sergeant, they usually would take the most gullible freshman in the outfit and they would, a little bit ahead of time, they'd start building this up.

that you know says this outfit's getting kind of rank and it needs somebody to really keep things going and keep things under control and says we just don't seem to have anybody to do that and we're going to have to get us a fish sergeant.
And they would always pick in an outfit
the most gullible person that they could find and tell him that he was, make him fish sergeant.
And they'd say, now listen, when you're fish sergeant, you have senior privileges.
You do whatever you want to, but you do have to keep order.
And then they would stage a little set to at which time
he'd really catch hell because they'd stage a little fight, but they'd really let him have it.
That's about it there in the mess hall.
Describe a, let's see, in mess hall, did you all have cush questions?
No, not to my knowledge.
Now, I've heard in the 50s that that was a ritual.
And for you as a fish, even once cush was available to freshmen, before you got your cush, you had to answer a question for which they would have movable answers.
One of the favorites was, how many stars are there in the Texas flag?
And if you answered one, they said, no, there's two.
There's one on each side.
And if you said two, they'd say, no, there's one.
It goes all the way through.
So you still didn't get your cook.
Let's see.
Describe a typical day, class day.
What time did you get up?
What happened all the way through that day?
Okay.
Reveille.
If I'm not mistaken, Reveille was usually about a quarter to seven, or seven, right around that time.
However, as a freshman, you had to get up and go clean.
You were a maid for an upperclassman, or maybe two upperclassmen, depending.
When the semester started,
that each upperclassman's room had two, but as the freshmen thinned out, got down to where one guy had one room, I cleaned up for a couple of seniors.
Well, no, I started out cleaning up for two juniors, and it was wonderful.
They were great guys.
They weren't as tied up in getting on the freshmen as most people were.
And they were both, they both liked athletics.
And I always played on the intramural football and basketball and other teams.
We always worked together, so I had a good deal there.
Then I, freshman, I mean, seniors always had two-room orders, and one of those pairs of that, of one pair, they lost one, and I had to move and go take care of that fellow.
So anyway, that was early in the morning, and then you'd,
after you got their room cleaned up and you'd come and fix your own then you'd fall out and you'd march to breakfast.
You always marched to the mess hall but then came back to your room and for the most part from after breakfast until you went to class if you had an eight o'clock
there was no much going on.
You just got ready and went to class.
You had to have your schedule posted on the door of your room.
And when you weren't in class, you better be in that room so that you would be available
to run errands or whatever they wanted you to do.
And supposedly you could study at that time if you wanted to, but that was kind of out of the question.
The only time you could study is very rarely if everybody else was, all the sophomores were somewhere else.
If they didn't have another opportunity, they'd use you to amuse themselves in some way.
So you can more or less forget about studying in the daytime unless you were having problems with, real problems with a course.
And you could always go to the seniors and they would get a quietus and, but you better not be lying about it.
You better be telling.
And we had, in the afternoons, well,
in the afternoons.

One afternoon we had a drill and there just wasn't a lot of time, intramural practice or intramural things and then by that time it's time to get back and go to eat and then come back and then get in your room and that is about it.
There was, we left
We didn't go out at nights except to yell practice or something special.
At that time we went to Guyon Hall for different features.
Where could you during the day go outside the dormitory to study?
Yes, if you'd have to get permission.
And you could get permission supposedly to go to the library.
But boy, if you signed out to go to that library, you better be there.
If you got caught, you got your ass beat.
This was not supposed to be going on, well I don't guess it ever was supposed to be going on, but it was still going on in 1941, I'll tell you.
The paddling.
Describe one of those sessions.
Where did it happen and who did it, who was there?
Well, in our outfit, they took the board privileges away from the sophomores.
And it was practically all administered by a senior or a junior.
And we had some done by sophomores, but who's going to turn him in?
And it was a normal deal.
But when they told you to grab a pooch, well you reached down and got ahold of your trout and pulled it up, your butt as tight as it was, and you usually got three hits.
And the paddle was made out of what?
Wood.
So they weren't using bats?
Oh, no, no, I never.
I've heard those stories and they could have taken place, but during my time they had some elaborate boards, baby, but they were boards.
They were not what the bat, no, and it was flat.
And this happened in the hallway?
Usually in the hallway, uh-huh.
The hallway or in the bathroom.
You know, we had big bathrooms over there.
And there were a good number of witnesses?
Oh, yes, always.
At least, well, when I say a good number, at least two people there witnessing it.
Do you remember any freshman pranks, jokes, good bull your first year?
Well, I don't.
We had a couple of guys that weren't real popular in our outfit, and I've been ashamed of this, but I'm going to tell you anyway.
When we would go down and have, just before taps, we'd go out and have a little yell practice
battery area.
And we were usually out there about fifteen minutes, from tattoo to taps, ten minutes, whatever it was.
Well, when we went out there that evening, another fellow and myself went in these boys'
And we did open their closet doors and take all their shoes and put them up on the bed.
And then we, in the laboratory that was there, had the plug in the bottom, and the overflow deal, we stuffed it with the deal and turned on both water spigots all the way, you know.
I mean this wasn't anything original, but it was the only time it had happened in that dormitory that year.
And then we'd go out and we'd put a towel down there so when the door was closed, water wouldn't run under the deal.
I don't say some didn't seep, but there wasn't much running.
Well, you can't believe, or maybe you can believe, how much water in 10 to 15 minutes can accumulate in a room that size.
And I'm telling you, when they came back, they couldn't hardly open that door.
It swung to the inside, you see.
And when they did get that thing open and water comes
out and down the hall and down the steps and down to the bottom.
And it was funny, but it was not funny.
Were these, now were the victims sophomores?
No, the victims were freshmen.
Oh, they were freshmen, okay.
And they were a couple of freshmen that, you know, you punished your own, you took care of your own.
I really was kind of a... Now were the guilty parties in this ever discovered?
No, no, no, no.
And the freshmen had to clean up their own room?
Well, no, every freshman had to help.
Oh, okay.
Because if it would have just been their room, it would have been one thing, but it came out and down the hall and everything else, you see.
But anyway, I mean a lot of people had
Pretty good idea who it was, but there was no real accusations ever made.
All right.
Still that first fall, do you remember your first Yale practice, midnight Yale practice?
I don't necessarily remember my first one, but I do, we had, I remember my first air out.
Are you familiar with air out?
Describe that.
All right.
I found out later, we didn't know at the time, and you know there's always somebody in an outfit or something that their brother had gone to A&M or their uncle or old friend or something.
And a lot of them had previous information that some of us others didn't have.
Sometimes they were a little reluctant to pass it on.
But anyway, before the first home game, we'd have an air out, which they called an air out.
Well, it wasn't too bad for me.
I was living on the second floor.
I could go right out that window, but those third floor boys, they had to come back and go down the steps and all that kind of stuff.
But first thing you do about it, you heard somebody yell, air out freshmen.
And I mean, they had belts and things like that, you know, and popping them around.
And we, my roommate and I had a little previous knowledge that there was going, that was going to take place.
And we were ready.
And when they,
when we heard the first noise, we had our titty shoes on and we went right out that window on that second floor.
And we, you didn't show up until the next morning, you know.
But Yale practice was a great thing.
Where was it held?
Over in front of Goodwin, Goodwin Hall at that time.
Goodwin Hall.
Now, was it a midnight yell practice?
Was it held that late?
No.
It was usually around noon.

rent seven thirty on friday nights right before the game and so the primary wait a minute excuse me just meant it was on friday night for home game for home games and the people who were there were almost core students only because there weren't many there would be a few teachers instructors and so on and so forth and a few girls but not many out of town dates
No, there might have been a few, but I hardly remember any because the girls that came to home games usually didn't arrive until Saturday.
Do you remember going to those first home football games?
What was that like?
It was a revelation to me to go and stand up at a football game all the time.
